This study is investigating the effects of persistent driven exercise in females aged 14-22 with and without eating disorders. Physical Activity is thought to change psychological and biological systems associated with reward and threat, which can lead to driven exercise in some people. We are investigating how biological and psychological systems are impacted by exercise. 
 
Participants in the study will come to the Psychiatry Department at the University of Wisconsin for three separate visits. During the first visit, we will go over a consent form that describes the study in more detail. You may ask as many questions as you like about the study.  If you decide to take part in the study and sign the consent form, we will complete a structured, clinical interview and a series of questionnaires. These interviews and questionnaires will ask questions about eating disorder symptoms you might have experienced and also ask about mental health and other behaviors. The purpose of this assessment is to determine eligibility for the study and to understand whether differences in health symptoms are related to certain cognitions and behaviors. This visit takes ~3 hours. Following this visit, you will be given an accelerometer to wear for 7 days to track your activity and sleeping patterns.  
 
You will be asked to complete three additional study visits following the initial intake if you are eligible for the study. 

On some study visit days, we will ask you to not eat from 1-4pm, and we will provide you with a nutritional supplement as a snack before your visit at 4pm, so that you feel energized and not hungry during your visit.  Tasks that you will be asked to do during some study visits include: 
1. completing  questionnaires about your mood and behaviors
2. taking part in a food challenge where you will be asked to drink a milk shake
3. Providing a sample of your blood via a blood draw
4. Exercising  or resting for ~30 minutes 
   
You will be compensated for your time participating. Your total compensation would be $200 over multiple visits if you complete all study procedures.  
 
You do not need to make a decision about joining the study right now. If you think you might be interested, we would like to ask you some questions today to see if you are eligible to begin the study. The questions will take about 5-10 minutes. We will ask you about your medical history, history of eating disorder symptoms, some psychological symptoms, HIV status, and demographic information.  You can stop answering questions at any time.  Choosing not to answer screening questions will not affect any treatment relationship you have with healthcare providers at UW-Madison, UW Health or any affiliated organizations, or any services you receive from them.   
 
If you are eligible to begin, we will make an appointment with you to meet with us at UW to tell you more information about the study and answer all of your questions.  At the time of the appointment or later, you can make a decision about whether you want to participate in the study or not. 
 
If you are eligible and decide to participate in the study, we will keep the information you provide during this screening along with the other information we collect during the study.  We will remove your name and contact information and label your information with a unique study code. Your name and contact information will be stored separately in a secured location with only study personnel having access to it so that we can contact you. We will ask your permission if you come into the study to keep your identifying information so that we can contact you for future studies, and we will destroy the identifying information after the study if you chose to not be contacted for future studies.
